<h1>Basic Sentence Patterns</h1>

<h2> <a name="AwaBdesu"> @N1{{}}@HI{{ha}}@N2{{}}@HI{{desu}}</a> </h2>

<p>
In this pattern <a href="grammar-particle-wa.html">@HI{{ha}}</a> marks the topic of the sentence, the remainder of
the sentence offers information about the topic. To make a predicate, a noun needs to be followed by a form of the 
<a href="grammar-copula.html">copula</a>; in
this case @HI{{desu}} is used as this is a polite sentence. For a negative sentence @HI{{desu}} would be
replaced by @HI{{jaarimasenn}}.

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{private}}ha @KT{{maiku mira-}}desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I am Mike Miller.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{private}}ha @KT{{enjinia}}desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I am an engineer.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{santos}}sanha@KJ{{study^life}}jaarimasenn.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Mr. Santos is not a teacher.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>
</p>

<p>
If @N2{{}} describes a place then this sentence pattern explains where a place, a thing or a person is.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{mountain^rice*field}}sanha@KJ{{matter^task^place}}desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Mr. Yamada is in the office.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h2> <a name="waga">~ @HI{{ha}} ~ @HI{{ga}}</a> </h2>

<p>
This construction relates a non-controllable state to a topic.

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{private}}<strong>ha</strong>@KJ{{England^word}}<strong>ga</strong>@KJ{{part}}karimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I understand English.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{flower^child}}<strong>ha</strong>@KJ{{eye}}<strong>ga</strong>kireidesu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Hanako has pretty eyes.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{resign^write}}<strong>ha</strong>@KT{{waxebusuta-}}<strong>ga</strong>iidesu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      As for dictionaries, Webster's is good.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>
</p>

